00:03:28.430 --> 00:03:29.540
That's unfortunate.

00:03:29.540 --> 00:03:31.530
You'd like a more
holistic organization,

00:03:31.530 --> 00:03:35.130
and one of the things we're
trying to do is to get there.

00:03:35.130 --> 00:03:38.390
One of the first things we did
as part of that is we set up

00:03:38.390 --> 00:03:38.890
Google+.

00:03:38.890 --> 00:03:43.470
Part of this was to
have a unified account

00:03:43.470 --> 00:03:46.600
system for all Google users.

00:03:46.600 --> 00:03:48.610
For example, I'll give
you something interesting

00:03:48.610 --> 00:03:49.600
you may not know.

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:51.099
On the third floor
of this building,

00:03:51.099 --> 00:03:53.642
we have a YouTube studio
and a lot of YouTube people.

00:03:53.642 --> 00:03:54.350
And it was great.

00:03:54.350 --> 00:03:56.160
We'd bring in
YouTube celebrities,

00:03:56.160 --> 00:03:59.270
and every now and again,
somebody would say, hey,

00:03:59.270 --> 00:04:01.740
do you know Google is
in the same building?

00:04:01.740 --> 00:04:04.540
And the YouTube guys
would go, well, yeah.

00:04:04.540 --> 00:04:06.150
They own us.

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:08.875
And then YouTube celebrities
would say, no way.

00:04:08.875 --> 00:04:09.750
We'd say, no, really.

00:04:09.750 --> 00:04:11.360
It happened several years ago.

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:12.935
And it turns out
people didn't know.

00:04:15.096 --> 00:04:17.470
One of the things we've been
doing with Google+ is trying

00:04:17.470 --> 00:04:20.339
to say, can we unify the
experience of Google so that

00:04:20.339 --> 00:04:23.020
if you use any of our services,
you have access to all of them

00:04:23.020 --> 00:04:24.660
as an end user?

00:04:24.660 --> 00:04:26.510
Also, how do we make
sure that if you

00:04:26.510 --> 00:04:29.220
want to use one of our
services or APIs or libraries,

00:04:29.220 --> 00:04:32.860
you should be able to use
that in any language--

00:04:32.860 --> 00:04:36.590
except Perl, because we
can't get volunteers.

00:04:36.590 --> 00:04:38.340
The idea is that you
should be able to use

00:04:38.340 --> 00:04:40.550
it web, iOS, Android,
it shouldn't matter.

00:04:40.550 --> 00:04:43.060
You should have access to it.

00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:45.930
So we're thinking about taking
the different platforms we've

00:04:45.930 --> 00:04:48.410
got and making
them work together

00:04:48.410 --> 00:04:50.482
so that we don't have
a Play console which

00:04:50.482 --> 00:04:52.440
is different from the
Google API console, which

00:04:52.440 --> 00:04:54.330
is different to how
YouTube does things.

00:04:54.330 --> 00:04:55.610
We want to fix that.

00:04:55.610 --> 00:04:57.620
We want to simplify this.

00:04:57.620 --> 00:05:00.150
Part of this is also
thinking about metrics,

00:05:00.150 --> 00:05:04.630
trying to change what we do so
it makes more sense for you.

00:05:04.630 --> 00:05:07.580
So let's try a little survey.

00:05:07.580 --> 00:05:10.600
When you guys are choosing
which games to build,

00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:13.532
working your games, putting
your games into production,

00:05:13.532 --> 00:05:14.740
what are the metrics you use?

00:05:14.740 --> 00:05:16.310
So shout out-- what
kind of metrics

00:05:16.310 --> 00:05:18.169
do you guys use to
measure the success

00:05:18.169 --> 00:05:19.210
or failure of your games?

00:05:22.040 --> 00:05:23.470
Retention, anything else?

00:05:26.624 --> 00:05:29.130
Up down?

00:05:29.130 --> 00:05:29.960
Virality.

00:05:29.960 --> 00:05:31.540
Anything else?

00:05:31.540 --> 00:05:32.040
Installs.

00:05:35.060 --> 00:05:37.570
Active users.

00:05:37.570 --> 00:05:40.150
Cold hard cash.

00:05:40.150 --> 00:05:41.880
That's a good metric.

00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:43.542
It's hard to game that metric.

00:05:43.542 --> 00:05:45.750
The point is, there's lots
and lots of these metrics,

00:05:45.750 --> 00:05:48.590
and as a platform, we need
to be asking ourselves,

00:05:48.590 --> 00:05:50.932
how do we help you
optimize these metrics?

00:05:50.932 --> 00:05:52.890
How do we help you make
sure that these numbers

00:05:52.890 --> 00:05:55.120
go up and to the right?

00:05:55.120 --> 00:05:58.390
Especially that cold
hard cash number.

00:05:58.390 --> 00:06:01.620
So what I'm going to do is talk
about the four sets of metrics

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:05.120
that we're currently
particularly focused on.

00:06:05.120 --> 00:06:07.970
Reach, user acquisition and
conversion, user engagement

00:06:07.970 --> 00:06:09.889
retention, and re-engagement.

00:06:09.889 --> 00:06:11.680
I'm just going to skim
this because we only

00:06:11.680 --> 00:06:13.504
have about 25 minutes left.

00:06:13.504 --> 00:06:15.670
But I just want to give you
a brief overview of some

00:06:15.670 --> 00:06:18.340
of the tools that are available
in Google+ and the way it hooks

00:06:18.340 --> 00:06:21.145
into the rest of Google
that you can take advantage

00:06:21.145 --> 00:06:25.170
of to optimize these metrics
or these sets of metrics.

00:06:25.170 --> 00:06:27.070
Let's start with reach.

00:06:27.070 --> 00:06:30.180
So you build something,
and we'd like

00:06:30.180 --> 00:06:33.600
you to reach as many
people as possible with it.

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:36.110
Well, for reach,
you've got to go

00:06:36.110 --> 00:06:38.950
for the biggest hammer we have.

00:06:38.950 --> 00:06:41.280
It's a little site
called google.com.

00:06:41.280 --> 00:06:43.460
You may have heard of it.

00:06:43.460 --> 00:06:45.740
The first and
fundamental problem

00:06:45.740 --> 00:06:48.900
you're going to have as a
game developer is nobody's

00:06:48.900 --> 00:06:50.491
heard of you.

00:06:50.491 --> 00:06:52.240
Or they've heard of
you, but they have not

00:06:52.240 --> 00:06:54.070
heard of your new game.

00:06:54.070 --> 00:06:55.790
So for example, who
here can tell me

00:06:55.790 --> 00:06:58.815
all the Angry Birds games and
the difference between them

00:06:58.815 --> 00:07:00.030
all?

00:07:00.030 --> 00:07:00.530
Can you?

00:07:00.530 --> 00:07:01.235
AUDIENCE: I can.

00:07:01.235 --> 00:07:02.110
ADE OSHINEYE: Really?

