00:11:22.720 --> 00:11:26.050
ADE OSHINEYE: OK, something
attractive to draw them back.

00:11:26.050 --> 00:11:26.850
Rewards.

00:11:26.850 --> 00:11:28.710
There's a lot of
things you can do.

00:11:28.710 --> 00:11:31.760
But one of the
things we've added

00:11:31.760 --> 00:11:33.980
is a little feature
called Incremental Auth.

00:11:33.980 --> 00:11:36.520
And the reason we've added
this is because it turns out

00:11:36.520 --> 00:11:40.740
lots of people use YouTube and
a lot of other Google services,

00:11:40.740 --> 00:11:44.140
and sometimes you can use the
data in those other services

00:11:44.140 --> 00:11:47.100
to make your experience
better, more enriching.

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:49.690
So for example, you can
ask them after they've

00:11:49.690 --> 00:11:52.660
signed in-- so it's a separate
process-- you can say,

00:11:52.660 --> 00:11:54.410
can we have access to
your YouTube account

00:11:54.410 --> 00:11:58.560
because perhaps we'd like to
write YouTube videos to it?

00:11:58.560 --> 00:12:02.560
So that when you have that
great, wonderful, perfect round

00:12:02.560 --> 00:12:04.877
of Flappy Bird
when you get to 64,

00:12:04.877 --> 00:12:06.460
you can actually
capture the recording

00:12:06.460 --> 00:12:08.702
and share it on YouTube
so people can see

00:12:08.702 --> 00:12:11.010
you didn't cheat.

00:12:11.010 --> 00:12:14.260
If Rich had captured his
356 score with a video,

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:17.290
he could send that around
now to prove he didn't cheat.

00:12:17.290 --> 00:12:20.580
But he didn't, so we have
to believe he's cheating.

00:12:20.580 --> 00:12:23.680
Point being, this is a
separate section from sign in.

00:12:23.680 --> 00:12:26.610
And you could pull in
any Google APIs this way.

00:12:26.610 --> 00:12:30.520
So that means you could
do things like-- can we

00:12:30.520 --> 00:12:34.070
capture screenshots and maybe
share them to Drive, or are

00:12:34.070 --> 00:12:36.180
there things you
have in other Google

00:12:36.180 --> 00:12:39.070
properties that we can
use to augment this game?

00:12:39.070 --> 00:12:41.260
Typically, if it's a
music-related game,

00:12:41.260 --> 00:12:44.650
one thing you can do is
with the user's permission,

00:12:44.650 --> 00:12:48.680
go through their YouTube history
and use their musical tastes

00:12:48.680 --> 00:12:51.660
to influence the
nature of the game.

00:12:51.660 --> 00:12:54.590
The point is, from
the sign in flow,

00:12:54.590 --> 00:12:57.877
you could either ask for a
wide range of Google APIs,

00:12:57.877 --> 00:12:59.460
or you can ask for
them incrementally,

00:12:59.460 --> 00:13:02.057
and use those to enrich
the experience of the game.

00:13:02.057 --> 00:13:03.890
The point being, it
gives you an opportunity

00:13:03.890 --> 00:13:07.310
to personalize the game so
that you can see your face,

00:13:07.310 --> 00:13:09.870
your friends' faces, the
things that matter to you.

00:13:19.120 --> 00:13:20.200
You've got a game.

00:13:20.200 --> 00:13:22.110
You've got people,
they've signed in.

00:13:22.110 --> 00:13:23.930
They've brought their
social graph across.

00:13:23.930 --> 00:13:27.189
You've somehow made the
game engaging, enticing,

00:13:27.189 --> 00:13:28.855
interesting, because
you've personalized

00:13:28.855 --> 00:13:32.410
it using data you
have that's available

00:13:32.410 --> 00:13:36.220
about them from the full
range of Google services.

00:13:36.220 --> 00:13:38.060
How do I keep them engaged?

00:13:38.060 --> 00:13:39.560
How do I retain them?

00:13:39.560 --> 00:13:43.000
Well, if you've used any of the
Google Play games in the past,

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.290
you know that we have high
scores, we have leader boards.

00:13:46.290 --> 00:13:48.430
One of the really
nice things you can do

00:13:48.430 --> 00:13:50.390
that actually starts
to get very interesting

00:13:50.390 --> 00:13:53.882
is when I share that high
score, what do I share?

00:13:53.882 --> 00:13:55.340
Now, the typical
thing people do is

00:13:55.340 --> 00:13:59.300
they share just a
little blob of text.

00:13:59.300 --> 00:14:00.960
As you can see, I
scored zero points.

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:03.610
That's actually
unlocked an achievement.

00:14:03.610 --> 00:14:05.360
But nothing stops them
from editing there,

00:14:05.360 --> 00:14:08.320
cheating and saying yeah,
I scored 1,000 points,

00:14:08.320 --> 00:14:12.070
except for the screen shot,
which keeps me honest.

00:14:12.070 --> 00:14:13.780
The point being,
you can start to do

00:14:13.780 --> 00:14:15.620
these kinds of
interesting things

00:14:15.620 --> 00:14:19.320
to actually make the sharing
experience more compelling.

00:14:19.320 --> 00:14:22.320
Because Flappy Bird is
actually a pretty OK game,

00:14:22.320 --> 00:14:25.342
but what makes it great is
when you get a new high score

00:14:25.342 --> 00:14:26.800
and you take that
screenshot, which

00:14:26.800 --> 00:14:28.810
you have to do manually
in Flappy Bird,

00:14:28.810 --> 00:14:31.240
and then you share it to
the stream to tell people,

00:14:31.240 --> 00:14:32.287
look what I did.

00:14:32.287 --> 00:14:34.870
And somebody else sends you back
a message a few minutes later

00:14:34.870 --> 00:14:36.960
saying, look, I just
beat your score.

00:14:36.960 --> 00:14:39.010
And that gets you to come back.

00:14:39.010 --> 00:14:42.000
There's an authenticity that
comes from having the screen

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:46.720
shot, rather than me
claiming I got 1,000 points.

00:14:46.720 --> 00:14:48.650
So that's a much
more powerful system.

00:14:48.650 --> 00:14:52.470
So you have achievements,
but ultimately, the thing

00:14:52.470 --> 00:14:56.400
that gets you to come back
is, I had a great experience.

00:14:56.400 --> 00:14:58.790
Here's the proof of it, here's
the social proof of this.

00:14:58.790 --> 00:15:03.380
And I share that with people I
know, and then they come back.

00:15:03.380 --> 00:15:07.220
Because a lot of people will
try your game-- it's OK,

00:15:07.220 --> 00:15:11.150
it's great-- and then they
get bored or life intervenes,

00:15:11.150 --> 00:15:13.340
and then somebody
they know plays it,

00:15:13.340 --> 00:15:14.680
and then they come back.

00:15:14.680 --> 00:15:16.630
So Rich, for example,
has tried to quit

00:15:16.630 --> 00:15:19.150
Flappy Bird on
multiple occasions.

00:15:19.150 --> 00:15:22.230
And every time he does,
somebody beats his high score,

00:15:22.230 --> 00:15:24.320
and he has to come back.

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:28.820
It's like in-- what's that
mafia film? "The Godfather"?

00:15:28.820 --> 00:15:33.190
Just when you think you're
out, they pull you back in.

00:15:33.190 --> 00:15:36.122
Speaking of which,
re-engagement.

00:15:36.122 --> 00:15:40.430
Who here actually sends
re-engagement emails

00:15:40.430 --> 00:15:42.450
in their games?

00:15:42.450 --> 00:15:43.110
Hands up.

00:15:43.110 --> 00:15:44.200
Nobody?

00:15:44.200 --> 00:15:45.820
Come on, I play your games.

00:15:49.060 --> 00:15:52.910
Who here sends re-engagement
notifications telling people,

00:15:52.910 --> 00:15:54.580
you haven't played
